  <div id="grooming" class="scroll-mt-40">
    <CaptionedBlock heading="Grooming: Cotton in the Tropics" imageAlt="Coton de Tulear puppy having its cotton-textured coat combed" imageSrc={imgScene3} imagePosition="left">
      <p>Overseas Coton guides describe flowing floor-length show coats; ignore them, as every sensible Singapore owner does. In our humidity the Coton lives in a puppy cut, which brings the routine to a comb-through 2 to 3 times a week, always down to the skin, because cotton texture mats close to the body where a glance misses it, plus a salon trim every 4 to 6 weeks.</p>
      <p>Two tropics-specific habits: dry the coat properly after rainy walks, damp cotton is where trouble starts, and give the face its daily ten-second wipe to keep the white bright. Everything you need is in the starter kit.</p>
    </CaptionedBlock>
  </div>

  <CloudDivider fillClass="fill-[var(--color-mint-100)]" />
  <div id="health" class="scroll-mt-40">
    <CaptionedBlock heading="Coton Health: What We Check Before You Take One Home" imageAlt="Coton de Tulear puppy at a veterinary health check before going home" imageSrc={imgScene4} variant="mid">
      <p>Every Coton goes home vet-checked, vaccinated, dewormed, and microchipped. Health is the breed's superpower: the Coton is one of the soundest, longest-lived dogs in existence, and its 14-to-17-year expectancy is the proof. The short watch-list is standard small-breed fare: patellar luxation, sensible eye checks, and dental care in a small jaw, met with the day-one brushing habit.</p>
      <p>Feeding is simple: your puppy comes with the food it is already eating, and any change should be gradual over a week. For portioning guidance see the <a href="/learn/puppy-health" class="underline underline-offset-2 text-[var(--color-accent-hover)]">puppy health checks explained</a> guide.</p>
    </CaptionedBlock>
  </div>
  <CloudDivider fillClass="fill-[var(--color-mint-100)]" flip />

  <CaptionedBlock heading="Your Coton's First Week at Home" imageAlt="Coton de Tulear puppy settling into a set-up playpen during its first week home" imageSrc={imgScene5} imagePosition="left">
    <p>Day 0: we deliver, free, at a time that suits you, usually morning or evening. The playpen, bed, water, and toys are set up before your Coton explores the room, and we walk you through all 30+ starter-kit items in person. Learn more about <a href="/delivery" class="underline underline-offset-2 text-[var(--color-accent-hover)]">how our free home delivery and setup works</a>.</p>
    <p>Days 1 to 3: keep it calm and close. This breed settles through proximity: the playpen where it can see people, a fixed feeding routine, and the toilet pads where we placed them. The chatty little vocalisations start early; enjoy them, they're the breed introducing itself.</p>
    <p>Days 4 to 7: the routine sticks, and two habits start now: book your free first lesson with an AVS-certified trainer, and practise short, boring departures, five minutes at a time, because a company-first breed's alone-time skills are built early or not at all. See <a href="/free-training" class="underline underline-offset-2 text-[var(--color-accent-hover)]">what the free AVS-certified training lesson covers</a>.</p>
  </CaptionedBlock>

